            <a name="redflags"></a>
            <p>There are many <b>red flags</b> that can reveal an abuser in your partners and there are also many tricks and clear behaviors that may indicate a potential batterer. <br><br><b>Do you recognize any of the followings?</b></p>

            <p>
            <ol>
                <li>Building you up, then breaking you down and repeating this cycle.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Quick involvement from the first dates, pressuring commitment in the relationship.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Extreme jealousy and possessive, following gender roles.</li> 
                <br>
                <li>Sarcastic comments downplayed as jokes.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Lack of respect for your feelings, to put you down.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Lack of trust in you.</li> 
                <br>
                <li>Denying their behavior.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Hypersensitivity. Feeling as though the whole world is against them, all the time.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Unreasonable statements about how much they deserve, or what they deserve.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Having a typically confrontational attitude.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Coercive behavior, or behavior that pressures you into things.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Giult tripping.</li>
                <br>
                <li>The silent treatment.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Lack of compromise. Unrealistic expectations.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Lying.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Constant checking in, needing to know where you are at all times.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Showing disrespect toward former partners.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Not taking responsibility for their actions, blaming you.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Breaking objects and sentimental possessions.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Expecting you to spend all of your time with him.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Sabotaging your friendships (isolation).</li>
                <br>
                <li>Interrogations about your day and whereabouts.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Cruelty toward others (e.g. animals, children).</li>
                <br>
                <li>Abusive actions in prior relationships.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Statements like, “If you loved me, you would do this and this.”</li>
                <br>
                <li>Subtle control, such as strongly encouraging you to dress a certain way.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Verbal abuse.</li>
            </ol>

            <p>
                Abusers are used to deny their actions and responsibility. <br>After a dramatic event of violence they can change their behavior asking for forgiveness and promising love and respect. But such behavior is just a brief phase that makes harder for a woman to leave her abusive partner, but unfortunately it will fall again in frictions and then another violent explosion. <br><br>For this reason it is critical to recognize the typical signs of abusive relationships.<br><br>
                <a name="phrases"></a>
                <b>In the following list some phrases that abusers are used to say to their partners:</b> 
            </p>

            <ol>
                <li>No one will ever want you.</li>
                <br>
                <li>You deserve it.</li>
                <br>
                <li>You are stupid.</li>
                <br>
                <li>It's not rape, you are my wife.</li>
                <br>
                <li>I don't remember doing that.</li>
                <br>
                <li>I am sorry.</li>
                <br>
                <li>I love you and it will never happen again.</li>
                <br>
                <li>I'll kill myself if you leave.</li>
                <br>
                <li>It didn't hurt that much.</li>
                <br>
                <li>You are too sensitive.</li>
                <br>
                <li>Why do you make me hurt you?</li>
                <br>
                <li>No one is going to believe you.</li>
                <br>
                <li>You are crazy.</li>
                <br>
                <li>You'd be more beautiful if...</li>
                <br>
                <li>I'm going to kill you.</li>
                <br>
                <li>If you leave me, I'll kill your family.</li>
                <br>
                <li>You're cheating on me.</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                <b>If you have ever experienced even some of the above, take action because you don’t deserve any of these!</b> You must live your life freely and happily.<br><br>
                <a name="important"></a>
            <h3>It is important to understand that:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Violence is never acceptable and it is a crime.</li>
                <br>
                <li>You have to <a href="http://4ramen.ap-southeast-2.elasticbeanstalk.com/tips.jsp" style="color: blue">take actions</a>, as with no intervention violence does not stop and can become more severe.</li>
                <br>
                <li>It is never your fault, you don't deserve violence and abuse.</li>
                <br>
                <li>There are <a href="http://4ramen.ap-southeast-2.elasticbeanstalk.com/search.jsp" style="color: blue">associations, organisations</a> that can help you.</li>
                <br>
                <li>There are laws that protect you.</li>

                <br>
                <p>Maybe you don’t know how to start, what <a href="http://4ramen.ap-southeast-2.elasticbeanstalk.com/tips.jsp" style="color: blue">precautions take</a> or where you can <a href="http://4ramen.ap-southeast-2.elasticbeanstalk.com/mapping.jsp" style="color: blue">ask for help</a>.
                    If you are in danger, always call 000 or 1800RESPECT.
                </p>
